\m
\c  18  
\b
\p
\v 1 When Jesus had said this, he went out with his disciples and crossed the Kidron ravine to a place where there was a garden, into which he and his disciples went. 
\v 2 The place was well known to Judas, the betrayer, for Jesus and his disciples had often met there. 
\v 3 So Judas, who had obtained the soldiers of the Roman garrison, and some guards from the chief priests and the Pharisees, came there with lanterns, torches, and weapons. 
\v 4 Jesus, aware of all that was coming upon him, went to meet them, and said to them, \wj ‘\+w For\+w* \+w whom\+w* \+w are\+w* \+w you\+w* \+w looking\+w*?’\wj* 
\p
\v 5 ‘Jesus of Nazareth,’ was their answer. \wj ‘\+w I\+w* \+w am\+w* \+w he\+w*,’\wj* said Jesus. (Judas, the betrayer, was also standing with them.) 
\v 6 When Jesus said \wj “\+w I\+w* \+w am\+w* \+w he\+w*,”\wj* they drew back and fell to the ground. 
\v 7 So he again asked for whom they were looking, and they answered, ‘Jesus of Nazareth.’ 
\p
\v 8  \wj ‘\+w I\+w* \+w have\+w* already \+w told\+w* \+w you\+w* \+w that\+w* \+w I\+w* \+w am\+w* \+w he\+w*,’\wj* replied Jesus, \wj ‘\+w so\+w*, \+w if\+w* \+w it\+w* \+w is\+w* \+w for\+w* \+w me\+w* \+w that\+w* \+w you\+w* \+w are\+w* \+w looking\+w*, \+w let\+w* \+w these\+w* \+w people\+w* \+w go\+w*.’\wj* 
\v 9 This was in fulfilment of his words – \wj “\+w Of\+w* \+w those\+w* \+w whom\+w* \+w you\+w* \+w have\+w* \+w given\+w* \+w me\+w* \+w I\+w* \+w have\+w* \+w not\+w* lost \+w one\+w*.”\wj* 
\v 10 At this, Simon Peter, who had a sword with him, drew it, and struck the high priest’s servant, and cut off his right ear. The servant’s name was Malchus. 
\v 11 But Jesus said to Peter, \wj ‘Sheathe \+w your\+w* \+w sword\+w*. \+w Should\+w* \+w I\+w* \+w not\+w* \+w drink\+w* \+w the\+w* \+w cup\+w* \+w which\+w* \+w the\+w* \+w Father\+w* \+w has\+w* \+w given\+w* \+w me\+w*?’\wj* 
\b
\p
\v 12 So the soldiers of the garrison, with their commanding officer and the Jewish guards, arrested Jesus and bound him, 
\v 13 and took him first of all to Annas. Annas was the father-in-law of Caiaphas, who was high priest that year. 
\v 14 It was Caiaphas who had counselled the religious authorities, that it was best that one person should die for the people. 
\v 15 Meanwhile Simon Peter followed Jesus, and so did another disciple. That disciple, being well-known to the high priest, went with Jesus into the high priest’s courtyard, 
\v 16 while Peter stood outside by the door. Presently the other disciple – the one well-known to the high priest – went out and spoke to the portress, and brought Peter in. 
\v 17 So the maidservant said to Peter, ‘Aren’t you also one of this man’s disciples?’ 
\p ‘No, I am not,’ he said. 
\v 18 The servants and guards were standing round a charcoal fire (which they had made because it was cold), and were warming themselves. Peter, too, was with them, standing and warming himself. 
\v 19 The high priest questioned Jesus about his disciples and about his teaching. 
\v 20  \wj ‘\+w For\+w* \+w my\+w* \+w part\+w*,’\wj* answered Jesus, \wj ‘\+w I\+w* \+w have\+w* \+w spoken\+w* \+w to\+w* \+w all\+w* \+w the\+w* \+w world\+w* \+w openly\+w*. \+w I\+w* \+w always\+w* \+w taught\+w* \+w in\+w* \+w some\+w* \+w synagogue\+w*, \+w or\+w* \+w in\+w* \+w the\+w* \+w Temple\+w* Courts, places \+w where\+w* \+w everyone\+w* \+w assembles\+w*, \+w and\+w* \+w I\+w* \+w never\+w* \+w spoke\+w* \+w of\+w* \+w anything\+w* \+w in\+w* \+w secret\+w*.\wj* 
\v 21  \wj \+w Why\+w* \+w question\+w* \+w me\+w*? \+w Question\+w* \+w those\+w* \+w who\+w* \+w have\+w* listened \+w to\+w* \+w me\+w* \+w as\+w* \+w to\+w* \+w what\+w* \+w I\+w* \+w have\+w* \+w spoken\+w* \+w about\+w* \+w to\+w* \+w them\+w*. \+w They\+w* \+w must\+w* \+w know\+w* \+w what\+w* \+w I\+w* \+w said\+w*.’\wj* 
\v 22 When Jesus said this, one of the guards, who was standing near, gave him a blow with his hand. ‘Do you answer the high priest like that?’ he exclaimed. 
\v 23  \wj ‘\+w If\+w* \+w I\+w* \+w said\+w* \+w anything\+w* \+w wrong\+w*, \+w give\+w* evidence \+w about\+w* \+w it\+w*,’\wj* replied Jesus, \wj ‘\+w but\+w* \+w if\+w* \+w not\+w*, \+w why\+w* \+w do\+w* \+w you\+w* \+w strike\+w* \+w me\+w*?’\wj* 
\v 24 Annas sent him bound to Caiaphas the high priest. 
\v 25 Meanwhile Simon Peter was standing there, warming himself; so they said to him, ‘Aren’t you also one of his disciples?’ Peter denied it. ‘No, I am not,’ he said. 
\v 26 One of the high priest’s servants, a relation of the man whose ear Peter had cut off, exclaimed, ‘Didn’t I myself see you with him in the garden?’ 
\v 27 Peter again denied it; and at that moment a cock crowed. 
\b
\p
\v 28 From Caiaphas they took Jesus to the Government house. It was early in the morning. But they did not enter the Government house themselves, otherwise they might become defiled, and so be unable to eat the Passover. 
\v 29 Therefore Pilate came outside to speak to them. ‘What charge do you bring against this man?’ he asked. 
\v 30 ‘If he had not been a criminal, we should not have given him up to you,’ they answered. 
\v 31 ‘Take him yourselves,’ said Pilate, ‘and try him by your own Law.’ 
\p ‘We have no power to put anyone to death,’ the authorities replied – 
\v 32 in fulfilment of what Jesus had said when indicating the death that he was destined to die. 
\v 33 After that, Pilate went into the Government house again, and calling Jesus up, asked him, ‘Are you the king of the Jews?’ 
\p
\v 34  \wj ‘\+w Do\+w* \+w you\+w* \+w ask\+w* \+w me\+w* \+w that\+w* \+w yourself\+w*?’\wj* replied Jesus, \wj ‘\+w or\+w* \+w did\+w* others \+w say\+w* \+w it\+w* \+w to\+w* \+w you\+w* \+w about\+w* \+w me\+w*?’\wj* 
\p
\v 35 ‘Do you take me for a Jew?’ was Pilate’s answer. ‘It is your own nation and the chief priests who have given you up to me. What have you done?’ 
\p
\v 36  \wj ‘\+w My\+w* kingly power,’\wj* replied Jesus, \wj ‘\+w is\+w* \+w not\+w* due \+w to\+w* \+w this\+w* \+w world\+w*. \+w If\+w* \+w it\+w* \+w had\+w* \+w been\+w* \+w so\+w*, \+w my\+w* \+w servants\+w* \+w would\+w* \+w be\+w* doing \+w their\+w* utmost \+w to\+w* prevent \+w my\+w* \+w being\+w* \+w given\+w* \+w up\+w* \+w to\+w* \+w the\+w* authorities; \+w but\+w* \+w my\+w* kingly power \+w is\+w* \+w not\+w* \+w from\+w* \+w the\+w* \+w world\+w*.’\wj* 
\p
\v 37 ‘So you are a king after all!’ exclaimed Pilate. \wj ‘Yes, \+w it\+w* \+w is\+w* \+w true\+w* \+w I\+w* \+w am\+w* \+w a\+w* \+w king\+w*,’\wj* answered Jesus. \wj ‘\+w I\+w* \+w was\+w* \+w born\+w* \+w for\+w* \+w this\+w*, \+w I\+w* \+w have\+w* \+w come\+w* \+w into\+w* \+w the\+w* \+w world\+w* \+w for\+w* \+w this\+w* – \+w to\+w* \+w bear\+w* \+w testimony\+w* \+w to\+w* \+w the\+w* truth. \+w Everyone\+w* \+w who\+w* \+w is\+w* \+w on\+w* \+w the\+w* \+w side\+w* \+w of\+w* truth listens \+w to\+w* \+w my\+w* \+w voice\+w*.’\wj* 
\p
\v 38 ‘What is truth?’ exclaimed Pilate. After saying this, he went out to the crowd again, and said, ‘For my part, I find nothing with which he can be charged. 
\v 39 It is, however, the custom for me to grant you the release of one man at the Passover Festival. Do you wish for the release of the king of the Jews?’ 
\p
\v 40 ‘No, not this man,’ they shouted again, ‘but Barabbas!’ This Barabbas was a robber. 
\c 19  
\b
\p
\v 1 After that, Pilate had Jesus scourged. 
\v 2 The soldiers made a crown with some thorns and put it on his head and threw a purple robe round him. 
\v 3 They kept coming up to him and saying, ‘Long live the king of the Jews!’ and they gave him blow after blow with their hands. 
\v 4 Pilate again came outside, and said to the people, ‘Look! I am bringing him out to you, so that you may know that I find nothing with which he can be charged.’ 
\v 5 Then Jesus came outside, wearing the crown of thorns and the purple robe; and Pilate said to them, ‘Here is the man!’ 
\v 6 When the chief priests and the guards saw him, they shouted, ‘Crucify him! Crucify him!’ 
\p ‘Take him yourselves and crucify him,’ said Pilate. ‘For my part, I find nothing with which he can be charged.’ 
\p
\v 7 ‘But we,’ replied the crowd, ‘have a Law, under which he deserves death for making himself out to be the Son of God.’ 
\v 8 When Pilate heard what they said, he became still more alarmed; 
\v 9 and, going into the Government house again, he said to Jesus, ‘Where do you come from?’ 
\v 10 But Jesus made no reply. So Pilate said to him, ‘Do you refuse to speak to me? Don’t you know that I have power to release you, and have power to crucify you?’ 
\p
\v 11  \wj ‘\+w You\+w* \+w would\+w* \+w have\+w* \+w no\+w* \+w power\+w* \+w over\+w* \+w me\+w* \+w at\+w* \+w all\+w*,’\wj* answered Jesus, \wj ‘\+w if\+w* \+w it\+w* \+w had\+w* \+w not\+w* \+w been\+w* \+w given\+w* \+w you\+w* \+w from\+w* above; \+w and\+w*, \+w therefore\+w*, \+w the\+w* \+w man\+w* \+w who\+w* \+w betrayed\+w* \+w me\+w* \+w to\+w* \+w you\+w* \+w is\+w* guilty \+w of\+w* \+w the\+w* \+w greater\+w* sin.’\wj* 
\v 12 This made Pilate anxious to release him; but the crowd shouted, ‘If you release that man, you are no friend of the Emperor! Anyone who makes himself out to be a king is setting himself against the Emperor!’ 
\v 13 On hearing what they said, Pilate brought Jesus out, and took his seat on the Bench at a place called “The Stone Pavement” – in Hebrew “Gabbatha.” 
\v 14 It was the Passover Preparation day, and about noon. Then he said to the crowd, ‘Here is your king!’ 
\v 15 At that the people shouted, ‘Kill him! Kill him! Crucify him!’ 
\p ‘What! Should I crucify your king?’ exclaimed Pilate. ‘We have no king but the Emperor,’ replied the chief priests; 
\v 16 so Pilate gave Jesus up to them to be crucified. 
\b
\p So they took Jesus; 
\v 17 and he went out, carrying his cross himself, to the place which is named from a skull, or, in Hebrew, Golgotha. 
\v 18 There they crucified him, and two others with him – one on each side, and Jesus between them. 
\v 19 Pilate also had these words written and put up over the cross – “JESUS OF NAZARETH, THE KING OF THE JEWS.” 
\v 20 These words were read by many people, because the place where Jesus was crucified was near the city; and they were written in Hebrew, Latin and Greek. 
\v 21 The chief priests said to Pilate, ‘Do not write “The king of the Jews”, but write what the man said – “I am the king of the Jews.”’ 
\v 22 But Pilate answered, ‘What I have written, I have written.’ 
\b
\p
\v 23 When the soldiers had crucified Jesus, they took his clothes and divided them into four shares – a share for each soldier – and they took the coat also. The coat had no seam, being woven in one piece from top to bottom. 
\v 24 So they said to one another, ‘Do not let us tear it, but let us cast lots for it, to see who will have it.’ This was in fulfilment of the words of scripture – 
\q1 “They shared my clothes among them, 
\q2 and over my clothing they cast lots.” 
\m That was what the soldiers did. 
\v 25 Meanwhile near the cross of Jesus were standing his mother and his mother’s sister, as well as Mary the wife of Clopas and Mary of Magdala. 
\v 26 When Jesus saw his mother, and the disciple whom he loved, standing near, he said to his mother, \wj ‘\+w There\+w* \+w is\+w* \+w your\+w* \+w son\+w*.’\wj* 
\v 27 Then he said to that disciple, \wj ‘\+w There\+w* \+w is\+w* \+w your\+w* \+w mother\+w*.’\wj* And from that very hour the disciple took her to live in his house. 
\b
\p
\v 28 Afterwards, knowing that everything was now finished, Jesus said, in fulfilment of the words of scripture, \wj ‘\+w I\+w* \+w am\+w* \+w thirsty\+w*.’\wj* 
\v 29 There was a bowl standing there full of common wine; so they put a sponge soaked in the wine on the end of a hyssop-stalk, and held it up to his mouth. 
\v 30 When Jesus had received the wine, he exclaimed, \wj ‘\+w All\+w* \+w is\+w* \+w finished\+w*!’\wj* Then, bowing his head, he resigned his spirit to God. 
\v 31 It was the Preparation day, and so, to prevent the bodies from remaining on the crosses during the Sabbath (for that Sabbath was a great day), the Jews asked Pilate to have the legs broken and the bodies removed. 
\v 32 Accordingly the soldiers came and broke the legs of the first man, and then those of the other who had been crucified with Jesus; 
\v 33 but, on coming to him, when they saw that he was already dead, they did not break his legs. 
\v 34 One of the soldiers, however, pierced his side with a spear, and blood and water immediately flowed from it. 
\v 35 This is the statement of one who actually saw it – and his statement may be relied on, and he knows that he is speaking the truth – and it is given in order that you also may be convinced. 
\v 36 For all this happened in fulfilment of the words of scripture – “Not one of its bones will be broken.” 
\v 37 And there is another passage which says – “They will look on him whom they pierced.” 
\v 38 After this, Joseph of Arimathea, a disciple of Jesus – but a secret one, owing to his fear of the religious authorities – begged Pilate’s permission to remove the body of Jesus. Pilate gave him leave; so Joseph went and removed the body. 
\v 39 Nicodemus, too – the man who had formerly visited Jesus by night – came with a roll of myrrh and aloes, weighing nearly a hundred pounds. 
\v 40 They took the body of Jesus, and wound it in linen with the spices, according to the Jewish mode of burial. 
\v 41 At the place where Jesus had been crucified there was a garden, and in the garden a newly made tomb in which no one had ever been laid. 
\v 42 And so, because of its being the Preparation day, and as the tomb was close at hand, they laid Jesus there. 
\c 20  
\s1 The Risen Life 
\p
\v 1 On the first day of the week, early in the morning, while it was still dark, Mary of Magdala went to the tomb, and saw that the stone had been removed. 
\v 2 So she came running to Simon Peter, and to that other disciple who was Jesus’ friend, and said to them, ‘They have taken away the Master out of the tomb, and we do not know where they have laid him!’ 
\v 3 So, Peter started off with that other disciple, and they went to the tomb. 
\v 4 The two began running together; but the other disciple ran faster than Peter, and reached the tomb first. 
\v 5 Stooping down, he saw the linen wrappings lying there, but did not go in. 
\v 6 Presently Simon Peter came following behind him, and went into the tomb; and he looked at the linen wrappings lying there, 
\v 7 and the cloth which had been on Jesus’ head, not lying with the wrappings, but rolled up on one side, separately. 
\v 8 Then the other disciple, who had reached the tomb first, went inside too, and he saw for himself and was convinced. 
\v 9 For they did not then understand the passage of scripture which says that Jesus must rise again from the dead. 
\v 10 The disciples then returned to their companions. 
\p
\v 11 Meanwhile Mary was standing close outside the tomb, weeping. Still weeping, she leant forward into the tomb, 
\v 12 and perceived two angels clothed in white sitting there, where the body of Jesus had been lying, one where the head and the other where the feet had been. 
\v 13 ‘Why are you weeping?’ asked the angels. ‘They have taken my Master away,’ she answered, ‘and I do not know where they have laid him.’ 
\v 14 After saying this, she turned round, and looked at Jesus standing there, but she did not know that it was Jesus. 
\v 15  \wj ‘\+w Why\+w* \+w are\+w* \+w you\+w* \+w weeping\+w*? \+w Whom\+w* \+w are\+w* \+w you\+w* \+w seeking\+w*?’\wj* he asked. Supposing him to be the gardener, Mary answered, ‘If it was you, Sir, who carried him away, tell me where you have laid him, and I will take him away myself.’ 
\p
\v 16  \wj ‘\+w Mary\+w*!’\wj* said Jesus. She turned round, and exclaimed in Hebrew, ‘Rabboni!’ (or, as we should say, “teacher”). 
\v 17  \wj ‘\+w Do\+w* \+w not\+w* hold \+w me\+w*,’\wj* Jesus said, \wj ‘\+w for\+w* \+w I\+w* \+w have\+w* \+w not\+w* \+w yet\+w* \+w ascended\+w* \+w to\+w* \+w the\+w* \+w Father\+w*. \+w But\+w* \+w go\+w* \+w to\+w* \+w my\+w* brothers, \+w and\+w* \+w tell\+w* \+w them\+w* \+w that\+w* \+w I\+w* \+w am\+w* ascending \+w to\+w* \+w him\+w* \+w who\+w* \+w is\+w* \+w my\+w* \+w Father\+w* \+w and\+w* \+w their\+w* \+w Father\+w*, \+w my\+w* \+w God\+w* \+w and\+w* \+w their\+w* \+w God\+w*.’\wj* 
\v 18 Mary of Magdala went and told the disciples that she had seen the Master, and that he had said this to her. 
\b
\p
\v 19 In the evening of the same day – the first day of the week – after the doors of the room, in which the disciples were, had been shut because they were afraid of the religious authorities, Jesus came and stood among them and said, \wj ‘\+w Peace\+w* \+w be\+w* \+w with\+w* \+w you\+w*’;\wj* 
\v 20 after which he showed them his hands and his side. The disciples were filled with joy when they saw the Master. 
\v 21 Again Jesus said to them, \wj ‘\+w Peace\+w* \+w be\+w* \+w with\+w* \+w you\+w*. \+w As\+w* \+w the\+w* \+w Father\+w* \+w has\+w* \+w sent\+w* \+w me\+w* \+w as\+w* \+w his\+w* messenger, \+w so\+w* \+w I\+w* \+w am\+w* \+w sending\+w* \+w you\+w*.’\wj* 
\v 22 After saying this, he breathed on them, and said, \wj ‘\+w Receive\+w* \+w the\+w* \+w Holy\+w* \+w Spirit\+w*;\wj* 
\v 23  \wj if \+w you\+w* remit \+w anyone\+w*’s sins, \+w they\+w* \+w have\+w* \+w been\+w* remitted; \+w and\+w*, if \+w you\+w* \+w retain\+w* \+w them\+w*, \+w they\+w* \+w have\+w* \+w been\+w* \+w retained\+w*.’\wj* 
\b
\p
\v 24 But Thomas, one of the Twelve, called “The Twin,” was not with them when Jesus came; 
\v 25 so the rest of the disciples said to him, ‘We have seen the Master!’ 
\p ‘Unless I see the marks of the nails in his hands,’ he exclaimed, ‘and put my finger into the marks, and put my hand into his side, I will not believe it.’ 
\v 26 A week later the disciples were again in the house, and Thomas was with them. After the doors had been shut, Jesus came and stood among them, and said, \wj ‘\+w Peace\+w* \+w be\+w* \+w with\+w* \+w you\+w*.’\wj* 
\v 27 Then he said to Thomas, \wj ‘\+w Place\+w* \+w your\+w* \+w finger\+w* \+w here\+w*, \+w and\+w* \+w look\+w* \+w at\+w* \+w my\+w* \+w hands\+w*; \+w and\+w* \+w place\+w* \+w your\+w* \+w hand\+w* \+w here\+w*, \+w and\+w* \+w put\+w* \+w it\+w* \+w into\+w* \+w my\+w* \+w side\+w*; \+w and\+w* \+w do\+w* \+w not\+w* refuse \+w to\+w* \+w believe\+w*, \+w but\+w* \+w believe\+w*.’\wj* 
\v 28 And Thomas exclaimed, ‘My Master, and my God!’ 
\p
\v 29  \wj ‘\+w Is\+w* \+w it\+w* \+w because\+w* \+w you\+w* \+w have\+w* \+w seen\+w* \+w me\+w* \+w that\+w* \+w you\+w* \+w have\+w* \+w believed\+w*?’\wj* said Jesus. \wj ‘\+w Blessed\+w* \+w are\+w* \+w they\+w* \+w who\+w* \+w have\+w* \+w not\+w* \+w seen\+w*, \+w and\+w* \+w yet\+w* \+w have\+w* \+w believed\+w*!’\wj* 
\b
\p
\v 30 There were many other signs of his mission that Jesus gave in presence of the disciples, which are not recorded in this book; 
\v 31 but these have been recorded so that you may believe that Jesus is the Christ, the Son of God – and that, through your belief in his name, you may have life. 
\c 21  
\b
\p
\v 1 Later on, Jesus showed himself again to the disciples by the Sea of Tiberias. 
\v 2 It was in this way, – Simon Peter, Thomas, who was called “The Twin,” Nathanael of Cana in Galilee, Zebedee’s sons, and two other disciples of Jesus, were together, when Simon Peter said, 
\v 3 ‘I am going fishing.’ 
\p ‘We will come with you,’ said the others. They went out and got into the boat, but caught nothing that night. 
\v 4 Just as day was breaking, Jesus came and stood on the beach; but the disciples did not know that it was he. 
\v 5  \wj ‘\+w My\+w* \+w children\+w*,’\wj* he said, \wj ‘\+w have\+w* \+w you\+w* \+w anything\+w* \+w to\+w* eat?’\wj* 
\p ‘No,’ they answered. 
\v 6  \wj ‘\+w Cast\+w* \+w your\+w* \+w net\+w* \+w to\+w* \+w the\+w* \+w right\+w* \+w of\+w* \+w the\+w* \+w boat\+w*,’\wj* he said, \wj ‘\+w and\+w* \+w you\+w* \+w will\+w* \+w find\+w* \+w fish\+w*.’\wj* So they cast the net, and now they could not haul it in because of the quantity of fish. 
\v 7 The disciple whom Jesus loved said to Peter, ‘It is the Master!’ When Simon Peter heard that it was the Master, he fastened his coat round him (for he had taken it off), and threw himself into the sea. 
\v 8 But the rest of the disciples came in the boat (for they were only about a hundred yards from shore), dragging the net full of fish. 
\v 9 When they had come ashore, they found a charcoal fire ready, with some fish already on it, and some bread as well. 
\v 10  \wj ‘\+w Bring\+w* \+w some\+w* \+w of\+w* \+w the\+w* \+w fish\+w* \+w which\+w* \+w you\+w* \+w have\+w* \+w just\+w* \+w caught\+w*,’\wj* said Jesus. 
\v 11 So Simon Peter got into the boat and hauled the net ashore full of large fish, a hundred and fifty-three of them; and yet, although there were so many, the net had not been torn. 
\v 12  \wj ‘\+w Come\+w* \+w and\+w* \+w have\+w* breakfast.’\wj*, Jesus said. None of the disciples dared ask him who he was, because they knew it was the Master. 
\v 13 Jesus went and took the bread and gave it to them, and the fish too. 
\v 14 This was the third time that Jesus showed himself to the disciples after he had risen from the dead. 
\b
\p
\v 15 When breakfast was over, Jesus said to Simon Peter, \wj ‘\+w Simon\+w*, son \+w of\+w* \+w John\+w*, \+w do\+w* \+w you\+w* \+w love\+w* \+w me\+w* \+w more\+w* \+w than\+w* \+w the\+w* \+w others\+w*?’\wj* 
\p ‘Yes, Master,’ he answered, ‘you know that I am your friend.’ 
\p \wj ‘\+w Feed\+w* \+w my\+w* lambs,’\wj* said Jesus. 
\v 16 Then, a second time, Jesus asked, \wj ‘\+w Simon\+w*, son \+w of\+w* \+w John\+w*, \+w do\+w* \+w you\+w* \+w love\+w* \+w me\+w*?’\wj* 
\p ‘Yes, Master,’ he answered, ‘you know that I am your friend.’ 
\p \wj ‘Tend \+w my\+w* \+w sheep\+w*,’\wj* said Jesus. 
\v 17 The third time, Jesus said to him, \wj ‘\+w Simon\+w*, son \+w of\+w* \+w John\+w*, \+w are\+w* \+w you\+w* \+w my\+w* friend?’\wj* Peter was hurt at his third question being “Are you my friend?”; and exclaimed, ‘Master, you know everything! You can tell that I am your friend.’ 
\p \wj ‘\+w Feed\+w* \+w my\+w* \+w sheep\+w*,’\wj* said Jesus. 
\v 18  \wj ‘\+w In\+w* truth \+w I\+w* \+w tell\+w* \+w you\+w*,’ \+w he\+w* continued, ‘\+w when\+w* \+w you\+w* \+w were\+w* \+w young\+w*, \+w you\+w* used \+w to\+w* \+w put\+w* \+w on\+w* \+w your\+w* \+w own\+w* clothes, \+w and\+w* \+w walk\+w* \+w wherever\+w* \+w you\+w* \+w wished\+w*; \+w but\+w*, \+w when\+w* \+w you\+w* \+w have\+w* grown \+w old\+w*, \+w you\+w* \+w will\+w* \+w have\+w* \+w to\+w* \+w stretch\+w* \+w out\+w* \+w your\+w* \+w hands\+w*, \+w while\+w* someone \+w else\+w* puts \+w on\+w* \+w your\+w* clothes, \+w and\+w* takes \+w you\+w* \+w where\+w* \+w you\+w* \+w do\+w* \+w not\+w* \+w wish\+w*.’\wj* 
\v 19 Jesus said this to show the death by which Peter was to honour God, and then he added, \wj ‘\+w Follow\+w* \+w me\+w*.’\wj* 
\v 20 Peter turned round, and saw the disciple whom Jesus loved following – the one who at the supper leant back on the Master’s shoulder, and asked him who it was who would betray him. 
\v 21 Seeing him, Peter said to Jesus, ‘Master, what about this man?’ 
\p
\v 22  \wj ‘\+w If\+w* \+w it\+w* \+w is\+w* \+w my\+w* \+w will\+w* \+w that\+w* \+w he\+w* \+w should\+w* wait \+w until\+w* \+w I\+w* \+w come\+w*,’\wj* answered Jesus, \wj ‘\+w what\+w* \+w has\+w* \+w that\+w* \+w to\+w* \+w do\+w* \+w with\+w* \+w you\+w*? \+w Follow\+w* \+w me\+w* \+w yourself\+w*.’\wj* 
\v 23 So the report spread among his followers that that disciple was not to die; yet Jesus did not say that he was not to die, but said \wj ‘\+w If\+w* \+w it\+w* \+w is\+w* \+w my\+w* \+w will\+w* \+w that\+w* \+w he\+w* \+w should\+w* wait \+w until\+w* \+w I\+w* \+w come\+w*, \+w what\+w* \+w has\+w* \+w that\+w* \+w to\+w* \+w do\+w* \+w with\+w* \+w you\+w*?’\wj* 
\b
\p
\v 24 It is this disciple who states these things, and who recorded them; and we know that his statement is true. 
\b
\p
\v 25 There are many other things which Jesus did; but, if every one of them were to be recorded in detail, I suppose that even the world itself would not hold the books that would be written. 